'''Banking in Iceland''' faced a crisis in 2008, which resulted in the government taking over three of its largest [[commercial bank]]s.

The short-term liabilities of Icelandic banks in proportion to Iceland's [[GDP]] are 211%, as of 11 October 2008, or 480% of the country's national debt, and the average leverage ratio (assets/net worth) is 1 to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/11/business/worldbusiness/11charts.html|title=The World’s Banks Could Prove Too Big to Fail — or to Rescue|date=11 October 2008|work=The New York Times|accessdate=14 August 2016}}</ref>

