{{Politics of Belgium}}
The '''Belgian Law''' ({{lang-nl|Belgisch recht}}; {{lang-fr|Droit belge}}) is very similar to that of neighbouring [[France]], as a result of [[Belgium]] having adopted the [[Napoleonic code]] which governs French society. It also derives from the [[Constitution of Belgium]] and the [[European Convention on Human Rights]].

Due to a series of [[state reform in Belgium|state reforms in Belgium]], the country has been transformed from a unitary to a [[Federalism|federal]] state. Consequently, in addition to the federal level, the [[Communities, regions and language areas of Belgium|communities and regions]] have legislative authority in certain matters. Federal legislation is called a "law" whereas regional legislation is called a "[[Decree (Belgium)|decree]]" (''decreet, décret''), except for that of the [[Brussels-Capital Region]] which is called an "[[Ordinance (Belgium)|ordinance]]" (''ordonnantie, ordonnance''). 

