{{More citations needed|date=February 2015}} {{Politics of Moldova}}
A '''referendum on remaining an independent nation''' was held in [[Moldova]] on 6 March 1994.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip Stöver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1330 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> Initiated by President [[Mircea Snegur]], it was referred to as a "Consultation with the people" ({{lang-ro|La sfat cu poporul}}), and was approved by 97.9% of voters.<ref name=N1>Nohlen & Stöver, p1339</ref>
==Question== {{blockquote|Do you want the [[Republic of Moldova]] to develop as an independent and unitary state, in the frontiers recognized in the day where Moldova declared sovereignty, to promote a policy of neutrality and to maintain mutually-benefiting economic relations with all the countries of the world, and to guarantee its citizens equal rights, according to international law?}}
==Legality issues== The referendum was organized by a specially created republican commission after the Central Elections Commission refused to become involved.<ref name=N1/> However, its organization was in contravention of the 1992 referendums law, which stated that a referendum commission should have been formed by Parliament 60 days before the referendum, and no referendums should be held 90 days either side of elections (the [[Moldovan parliamentary election, 1994|parliamentary elections]] had been held a week earlier).<ref name=N1/>
==Results== {| class=wikitable style=text-align:right !Choice !Votes !% |- |align=left|For||1,722,602||97.9 |- |align=left|Against||36,546||2.1 |- |align=left|Invalid/blank votes||49,146||– |- |align=left|'''Total'''||'''1,808,294'''||'''100''' |- |align=left|Registered voters/turnout||2,407,964||75.1 |- |align=left colspan=3|Source: Nohlen & Stöver |}
==Aftermath== Many public figures and much of the press presented the referendum as a strong blow to the [[movement for unification of Romania and Moldova]] in both countries, despite the fact that the question did not refer directly to [[Romania]], but to independence. It also referred to territorial integrity, which was a main preoccupation due to the [[Transnistrian conflict]].
